“I’m signing you up for wrestling, because you need to play a sport where you can’t blame anyone when you get beat. It’s only you. You have to own it.” 

- @jayme.hardwick when she informed the boys (and me) that she had signed them up for the wrestling team. 

If you know my story, you know I exclusively wrestled in high school and didn’t play football until the 4th semester of college. 

—>I credit a massive amount of my success to the mindset and character I developed through wrestling. 

IMO Wrestling is the ultimate character builder. 

This event at a local high school was called a “friendly” meet. It was super cool. Kids weighed in, got their weight and age marked on their arm. Then they stood in a staging area and asked each other if they wanted to wrestle. They then walked over to the mat, stood in line and then proceeded to get after it. 

First off, I love the idea of kids asking another kid to wrestle. It takes some courage and social skills to be able to do that. And by asking someone to wrestle, there is a certain spirit of competition that is brought forward. A mutual respect. Really cool stuff. 

Lastly, for you wrestling folks out there, it was a no headlock tournament, which I think helps teach good habits to the kids. 

Anyways, I’m obviously super happy they’re wrestling. 😄

To get ahead of it… Get off my back! I will get them shoes, headgear and a singlet now. I had to make sure they liked it before I spent money on the gear!

For PERSPECTIVE:

I’ve been training hard for 26 years now, know what I’m doing in the weight room and in the kitchen…and this about as good as I can look. 

Sure…a little more deprivation and I can get a little leaner. I’m not going on stage in a pair of speedos, so that is really unnecessary. 

But I can’t really get MUCH more muscle than this, especially at my age (41). The older you get, the harder it gets to build muscle. 

I mean…I look fine, but certainly nowhere near what some of the people you and I follow on here look like. 

BTW…I’m totally cool with that and love how I feel, perform, and look. 

I say all that not to insight an “oh man, you look great” response. 

I say that to tell you that if you’re coming in to a health and fitness program in the New Year to GET YOUR MIND RIGHT!

I think it’s best to expect really slow results for an immense amount of effort. 

You’ll have to work harder, longer, and exhibit more discipline than you want or might think is possible for less results than you were wanting. 

This is not meant to discourage you. It’s intended to manage expectations. 

Expect it to be extremely hard, and it might seem easier. 

Accept less results for more work over a longer period of time, and you’ll likely increase your happiness with your progress. 

I’m not taking clients until the New Year, so we can get through this Holiday season before we get started together. If you’re interested in training with me, use the link in my bio and I’ll be in touch. 

Best,
Nick

I don’t train my clients to become mini-me’s. One of me is enough! 

That’s not what a good coach does. 

A good coach talks to their clients and works to understand who they are now, who they want to become, and tries to identify a path for them to become that. It requires listening for values, understanding prior diet and training history, and capabilities, identifying likes/dislikes, and meeting you where you are with the best available plan to help you get to where you’re trying to go…within reason. 

If I were to take the other approach and just give my training regimen to 99% of people, they’d get hurt, frustrated, and/or would most likely give up. 

While I KNOW that you can do ANY exercise program and lose weight, the intensity that I train at isn’t conducive for weight loss due to the amount of fatigue and soreness I accumulate on a consistent basis. I really put out! 

But Nick…Don’t we need to create a caloric deficit to lose weight? 

Yes…we do. But mostly that should be done with nutrition and non-exercise activity. The actual exercise certainly adds to it. But I have found that lots of folks over-estimate the calories burned from exercise and then over-consume calories to try to get their energy levels restored from a d-stomping session. 

That’s where a lot of frustration happens. The energy output is high. They’re suffering through workouts and then suffering through a caloric deficit. 

The reality is, if in a weight loss phase, we want to use the workouts more as a signaling mechanism to our body that…”hey, this dude wants to hold onto his muscle. We should burn the fat instead.” We don’t need to obliterate ourselves to maintain muscle. 

People who have been on a muscle maintenance plan will tell you that it doesn’t require that much effort to hold onto strength and muscle. 

I like to reserve the suffering in weight loss phases to the caloric restriction and keep the workouts shorter. 

Now…if you’re trying to build muscle—> that’s a different story altogether. You’ve got to GET AFTER IT in the weight room and take plenty of liberties with protein and calories in general. 

#healthcoach #thoughts #nutritionfirst #walkingsecond #workoutsthird

Anyways…We stock up on the BASICS…

BREAKFAST-eggs, oatmeal, fruit, protein shakes
LUNCH- deli meat for sandwiches
DINNER- check the video. We do something like this video a few times. We do save some meals for going out and enjoying the local fare. 
SNACKS- Greek yogurt, RTD protein shakes, nuts

—>I won’t do anything but bodyweight workouts to keep my fitness high and make sure I’m in a great mood. So that means there isn’t a need to fuel or refuel from those. I find the less I workout hard, the more weight I lose.

—>So these come back to my rules of weight loss.

1) Control your calories
2) Keep activity levels high

PUSH-UPS and HEART DISEASE

My buddy and strength mentor, @johnwelbourn @powerathleteinc had a post the other day about push-ups and heart disease. It sparked me to look it up and then subsequently try the challenge. 

So Harvard researchers did a fitness assessment on 1,104 firefighters. They did as many push-ups as possible in 1 minute. They also did a treadmill test. 

—>After 10 years, the researchers found that the men who could do more than 40 push-ups had a 96% lower risk than those who could only do 10 or fewer. 

—>And the more the better. 

And the researchers found that the push-ups were as good of a predictor of disease as the treadmill test. 

Thought it was a great piece of info and worth re-sharing. 

**Of note for me is the relationship between health and the strength to bodyweight ratio. Being big and strong is cool. But make sure you can handle your own bodyweight

Many misidentify this as ABNORMAL or think they lack the DISCIPLINE or WILL POWER. This simply isn’t true. The body is trying it’s best to return to HOMEOSTASIS at the level that it had grown accustomed to. 

So, rather than ALWAYS SWIMMING UPSTREAM, we go WITH THE CURRENT and RE-INTRODUCE MORE CALORIES back into their lives. We also ask that they pick up their activity levels and use the calories to INCREASE their FITNESS LEVELS. 

Also, naturally, with an INCREASE in CALORIES, the body will move more when not exercising and will have more energy to push harder when exercising. 

So it’s great. And then, NORMALLY, after a week or two at MAINTENANCE CALORIE levels, my clients are EAGER & MOTIVATED to commit to the CALORIE DEFICIT again. It works really well.

We’ve been banging the 100 Days to Football Challenge out with our team. It’s been really motivating. So thank you to everyone who is playing. Been fun watching you guys workout with your families. Hopefully you all are creating some fun memories and habits together. 

@jayme.hardwick turned me on to this simple style of training. She usually gives 15-20 minutes every day. She picks a body part or two and hammers them with 1-2 exercises. 

I generally like to work opposing muscle groups in the same plane of motion to avoid creating any imbalances.

So my spin on her workouts is something like this. 

Pick a body part and it’s opposite body part OR a movement and it’s counter-movement. Here are some ideas/concepts.
Chest/Rows
Incline Bench/Incline Bench Rows
Shoulder Press/Lat Pulls
Squats/Hinge

DON’T RUN FOR WEIGHT LOSS‼️

Here is why I don’t have my clients who need to lose more than 25lbs run to drop the weight. 👇

Before we get to it, for you skinny folks, imagine putting a 25, 50, or 100 pound weight vest on and taking a jog. Now that we’ve established what it feels like…

1) It’s hard on the joints! Running is a repetitive plyometric movement. The force placed on the joints when running is upwards of 2.5x bodyweight. So for a 300 lb man, that’s 750 lbs of pressure per step vs 1.2x bodyweight when walking. 

—>Add that up over time and it can cause some significant damage and lead to potential injury in the feet, ankles, knees, hips, and spine (where I feel it)!

2. For larger people with big ankles, it can be exhausting. Sure it can burn good calories, but I’ve found that most clients perceive distance running to be one of most difficult things to do (former lineman or folks with lineman-type frames aren’t built for distance running). This perception (or reality) oftentimes leads to overestimating calories and then underestimating calories consumed either as a reward or to repair/replenish. 

—> I know when I run distance all I can think about is a juicy burger, fries, and a milk shake. Not ideal for weight loss! 

3. I prefer to create a caloric deficit by keeping the calories consumed down, rather than continually trying to push the calories burned up. 

—> Many clients are surprised at how little they have to do to lose weight when they learn how to eat properly. 

—> The older we get, the more difficult and painful it becomes to try to outpace a bad diet. Obviously it DOES NOT WORK for a lot of people. 

I’m not poo poo-ing cardio. It is important for sure. There are plenty of lower impact ways to get it in without beating your body up to work your heart. 

But I would recommend getting your weight down BEFORE you start adding in runs. Your joints will thank you and I am willing to bet your weight loss will actually be expedited.

It’s counterintuitive I know. But my big-boned folks out there know what I’m talking about.

Dale: Dad, what are you doing? You said you were done lifting heavy things!

Dad: Son, it's single leg work. I have found it to be much safer than heavy bilateral work.

In all seriousness, l've never hurt my back doing heavy single leg work. EVER. Every time I've thrown out my back and put it into spasms (old man back), it's while doing square-stance bilateral (2-footed) work.

If you haven't noticed, one of my knees is kind of jacked. I had my entire lateral meniscus removed my rookie year ('04). 
It's got some funky arthritis building up on the inside and it caves in on the outside because there isn't any internal support. It will not lock out (can't get to full extension) and causes my left hip some issues because the effect is that one leg is shorter than the other.

There are lots of imbalances in my body that I'd prefer to know less about than more. Ignorance is bliss, right?

I just know that I still love to train legs and it's still important. I just can't do what I used to do and NOT throw my back out (probably because of these imbalances).

I guess this is a long-winded way of saying...if you love to train legs, but have back, knee, or hip injuries, try the single leg variations like...

•Split Squats of All Types
•Lunges of All Types
•Step-ups of All Types
•Sled Work of All Types
•Single Leg Dead Lifts

This unilateral work allows your body to give maximal effort with lower weight (risk), less spinal load, and allows that single side to deal with its own imbalances and weaknesses without recruiting the stronger dominant side.

Also, side by side with bilateral work, unilateral training holds its own. In most categories other than bilateral strength improvement (specificity of training principle), there are no statistical differences between the two when it comes to change of direction, jumping, or speed.
So choose what you want to do and can do safely.
